Data Manipulation

worldwide2 <- select(worldwide, -Position , Song = 'Track Name')
worldwide2 <- mutate(worldwide2, Song = tolower(Song))


songAttributes2 <- mutate(songAttributes, song_title = tolower(song_title))


newdata <- inner_join(songAttributes2, worldwide2, by = c("song_title" = "Song"))


sums <- group_by(newdata, song_title) %>% summarize(Streams = sum(Streams))



newdata2 <- newdata[!duplicated(newdata$song_title), ]

newdata2 <- select(newdata2, -X1, -Streams, -Date)


songs <- inner_join(newdata2, sums, by = "song_title")

songs_standard = mutate(songs, "pop" = rescale(songs$Streams, to = c(50, 100)), dnce = songs$danceability*100, acous = rescale(songs$acousticness, to = c(1, 100)), nrgy = energy*100, dB = loudness, dur = songs$duration_ms/1000, title=songs$song_title, artist=artist)

top50_2015 = filter(top50Country, year >= 2015)

Data Exploratory Analysis

To find how popularity can be predicted, I first use the top50 songs in different countries.During the attempt of deciding which variables are statistically important, I use linear regression. At first, R^2 is rather low and I remove some variables that are not related to popularity. From the results above we can see, the highest R^2 is only 0.15 and when we tried different polynomial dimensions for danceability, the rss is also very high.

Thus, I add the data frame which does not show popularity directly, but I standardize all these variables like dB(loudness), duration(in second unit), energy. Now I combine these two data frames and try some models.

Data Manipulation Part 2

songs_pop_com = bind_rows(select(top50_2015, "title", "artist", "dnce", "acous", "dur", "nrgy", "dB", "pop"), select(songs_standard, "title", "artist", "dnce", "acous", "dur", "nrgy", "dB", "pop"))


set.seed(42)

pairs(select(songs_pop_com, -title, -artist))

To see the relationship between each two variables, we draw the scatterplots. From the picture we can see that there are not obvious linear relationship between popularity and any other variables. However, there are linear relationship among predictors such that energy and dB, which can cause collinearity.

Since we do not see obvious linear relationship between any independent variable and popularity, we guess there are may be some polynomial relationship between independent variables and popularity. Thus, we tried several polynomial regression to see whether we can make the prediction better. We use residual sum of squares to see the prediction to see whether rss decreases in that model and if so, we go further to put the regression onto the test dataset. We judge the prediction level by Mean-squared error.

plot(pop)

Polynomial Regression

songs_pop_com<-na.omit(songs_pop_com)
train <-1:1000
songs.train <- songs_pop_com[train,]
songs.test <- songs_pop_com[-train,]

MSE = 243.02.Almost the same as before but slightly higher.

Since there are a lot of predictors in this model, once two or more predictors are highly correlated, linear regression will perform not very well. Our prediction results will have a high variance instead. Thus, we need to use some prediction models that can penalize unimportant predictors and predict better when there are many attributes. We tried lasso first.

Besides linear regression, I tried lasso regression which works well in the dataset that has a lot of predictors and some of them may not very important or has a low weight on the popularity.

To use lasso, I first use cross validation to decide which lambda can achieve the lowest mean squared error in train set. After we gain the optimized lambda (penalized parameter), we can apply it on the test dataset.

MSE=248.03. Slightly higher than the polynomial regression.

The mean squared error for the lasso regression decreases much compared to the linear regression model, which means we are on the right track but we still need to try more machine learning model to analyze the popularity and figure out what is the best.

Another regression method we use is random forest. The reason we turned into random forest is because of its model interpretability. The random forest algorithm works by aggregating the predictions made by multiple decision trees of varying depth. Every decision tree in the forest is trained on a subset of the dataset. Thus, this model can provide a reliable feature importance estimate. Also, the random forest model offers efficient estimates of the test error without incurring the cost of repeated model training by cross-validation.

MSE = 474.52. Random Forest performs worse than lasso and polynomial regression, but better than the linear and ridge regression.

summary

After trying all these machine learning models, we find that polynomial regression performs best when predicting the popularity. However, since the observations are rather small and we did not have enough information for the artists, the prediction error is rather high in our research. To make a better prediction, we had better have some popularity index for the artists, which intuitively should be important for the popularity of the songs.

Generally, our research is still helpful for companies or business events to decide whether to buy/use the song.

Artist/Genre Popularity by Location/Culture

We also took a look at popular genres and artists around the world during time periods. Specifically, we investigated these statistics during Christmas time, separating groups by languages spoke in the countries. This attempts to separate the data somewhat by culture, and indicate what the differences may be.

English Genres

australia <- filter(top50, 150 < X & X < 201)
canada <- filter(top50, 350 < X & X < 401)
usa <- filter(top50, 600 < X & X < 651)

english <- rbind(usa, canada, australia)

group_by(english, country) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = country, fill = top.genre)) + geom_bar() +
  scale_color_brewer(type = "div", palette = "BrBG") +
  ggtitle("Top Genres in English Speaking Countries") + ylab("Number of Songs") + xlab("Country")

Here, we can see that the sample of English speaking countries have very similar tastes in genres around Christmas time, with only small variations based on differences in the location itself, such as the larger volume “australian alternative rock” in Australia.
